\begin_layout Standard
The propagation of ultrashort laser pulses in nonlinear optical media is a central topic in modern photonics and nonlinear optics.
 In particular,
 femtosecond laser pulses exhibit complex dynamics due to the interaction between dispersion and nonlinear optical effects.
 These ultrashort pulses are widely used in applications such as optical communications,
 ultrafast spectroscopy and precision material processing.
 Accurate modeling of their propagation is therefore essential for understanding and optimizing such systems.
 A fundamental mathematical model that describes the evolution of ultrashort optical pulses in nonlinear dispersive media is the one-dimensional Nonlinear Schrödinger Equation (NLSE).
 This equation captures the balance between group velocity dispersion (GVD) and Kerr nonlinearity,
 which are the dominant physical mechanisms governing femtosecond pulse propagation in photonics media 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "key1,key2,key3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The evolution of ultrashort pulses is adequately described by the one-dimensional NLSE,
 which arises under the assumption of a slowly varying envelope and incorporates the dominant propagation mechanisms.
 In particular,
 the interplay between second-order dispersion and the Kerr nonlinearity gives rise to phenomena such as self-phase modulation and the formation of optical solitons.
 Despite its relative simplicity,
 the NLSE reproduces a wide range of nonlinear phenomena with high fidelity.
 Consequently,
 it has attracted significant research interest,
 and has been extensively investigated using a wide range of analytical and numerical methods,
 under appropriate boundary conditions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "key4,key5,key6"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
In recent years,
 computational intelligence approaches have introduced several methods for solving the NLSE,
 such as artificial neural networks.In the context of nonlinear optical pulse propagation,
 several machine learning techniques can be used to approximate solutions of the NLSE,
 discover symbolic representations of pulse dynamics,
 or optimize parameters governing femtosecond pulse evolution.
 By combining the physical modeling provided by the NLSE with the adaptive search capabilities these methods,
 it becomes possible to develop flexible computational frameworks for studying complex nonlinear phenomena.
 (ANAFORES EDO!!)
\end_layout

