\begin_layout Standard
In the current section,
 the theoretical framework used to solve the nonlinear Schrödinger equation for nonlinear dispersive media is presented.
 This equation provides a fundamental model for describing the propagation of ultrashort optical pulses in optical fibers and similar photonic structures (Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NLSE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Within this framework,
 the evolution of femtosecond pulses is governed by the combined effects of chromatic dispersion and the Kerr nonlinearity of the medium.
 Due to the extremely short temporal duration of femtosecond pulses,
 their propagation dynamics are strongly influenced by the interplay between these two mechanisms,
 which affects both the temporal shape and the spectral characteristics of the optical field during propagation.
 For the purposes of the present analysis,
 the equation is considered in its normalized form.
 This formulation allows the principal physical effects to be expressed through dimensionless parameters and facilitates the numerical treatment of the problem.
 
\end_layout

