\begin_layout Section
Conclusions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Conclusions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The numerical investigation of the normalized Nonlinear Schrödinger Equation provides valuable insight into the dynamics of nonlinear wave propagation in dispersive media.
 The analysis of the numerical results shows that the evolution of the wave field is characterized by a gradual attenuation and diffusion of energy both in space and time.
 In particular,
 in Figure 1 it is observed that the initially strongly localized energy distribution decreases significantly over time,
 while the intensity profile transforms into a smoother and weakly oscillating form.
 This indicates the influence of phenomena such as dispersion and damping,
 which lead to a loss of the initial energy concentration.
 At the same time,
 Figure 2 confirms that the solution of the normalized NLSE evolves in a way that combines spatial propagation and temporal decay.
 The strong initial fluctuations weaken as the propagation distance increases,
 while the solution tends to zero for large time values,
 maintaining the character of a locally localized pulse.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall,
 the results demonstrate that the interaction of dispersion,
 nonlinearity and potential damping leads to waveform smoothing and intensity attenuation,
 confirming the natural behavior of NLSE solutions in realistic propagation systems.
\end_layout

